Introduction

This lab explores the generation of recursive fractals through algorithmic design, beginning with randomized fractal trees and extending into geometric cross structures. By modifying branching rules and introducing elements of randomness or symmetry, we observe how simple recursive functions can produce highly complex and varied patterns. The work draws from mathematical concepts of self-similarity and natural variation to simulate both organic and geometric fractal forms.

1. Random Fractal Trees

The original fractal tree function follows a deterministic pattern, reducing the branch length by a fixed amount (shorten_by) and maintaining a constant branching angle. This creates a symmetrical and predictable structure. I've made one modification to introduce randomness in both the branch length reduction and the branching angle. By using random.uniform(), each iteration produces a slightly different tree shape, mimicking natural variations found in real trees. Additionally, I introduced a third branch at each recursive step, making the structure more complex and further enhancing its resemblance to natural fractal growth. This randomness makes the tree appear more organic and less rigidly structured. The modification aligns with Mandelbrotâ€™s concept of fractional Brownian motion, where natural patterns exhibit self-similarity with an element of randomness, as seen in mountain ranges and coastlines (Mandelbrot, 1983). By integrating randomness, the new function better represents the stochastic nature of real-world fractal structures. 


  # Define the random fractal tree function
  def build_random_tree(branch_length):
    if branch_length > 5:

        forward(branch_length)

        new_length = branch_length - random.uniform(branch_length/6, branch_length/3)

        angle = random.uniform(20,50)
        
        left(angle)

        build_random_tree(new_length)

        right(angle * 2)

        build_random_tree(new_length)

        left(angle)

        backward(branch_length)

  # Initialize the turtle
  initializeTurtle(initial_window_size=(800, 800))

  # Set up the turtle's starting position and orientation
  jump(400, 600)  # Starting position at the bottom center of the canvas
  face(0)
  color('green')  # Set the pen color

  # Draw the fractal tree
  build_random_tree(100)

  # Display the drawing
  show()

The two fractal trees in the figure below are generated using a randomized branching algorithm, illustrate the unpredictable nature of recursive growth with stochastic variations in branch length and angles. Each tree exhibits a unique yet self-similar structure, reflecting the natural complexity of organic forms. The added third branch increases the density, making the canopy appear fuller and more intricate. Due to the randomness in the code, no two trees are identical, reinforcing the concept of natural variability in fractal geometry.

2. Fractal Crosses & Analysis

Inspired by the fractal trees, I explored how similar recursive principles could be applied to geometric structures, leading to the development of fractal crosses. By modifying the tree-generating code, I experimented with different branching rules, orientations, and recursive depths to produce distinct variations of fractal crosses. The first variation maintains a simple and balanced structure. The second applies a more distributed branching pattern, forming a highly intricate and symmetric cross, closely resembling the Vicsek fractal, a well-known example of a box fractal (Weisstein, n.d.). These variations highlight the adaptability of fractal algorithms and how slight modifications in recursion parameters can dramatically alter geometric complexity.

Below, there are two examples of these structures, with their respective code described in detai.

2.1. First Cross

The code below uses Turtle graphics to produce a recursive fractal shaped like a cross. The build_cross_3(length) function moves the turtle forward and backward while turning at right angles, dividing each segment into smaller parts to build a self-similar design. As recursion deepens, the turtle creates smaller branches on each side, forming intricate sub-arms. The drawing begins at the lower center of the screen, oriented upward, and is traced in red. The final output is a symmetric figure where smaller crosses emerge from each arm, demonstrating recursion through geometric repetition. 


# Define the fractal cross function
def build_cross_3(length):
    if length > 1:
        forward(length)
        backward(length/3)
        left(90)
        build_cross_3(length/4)
        right(90)
        build_cross_3(length/3)
        right(90)
        build_cross_3(length/4)
        right(90)
        build_cross_3(2*length/3)
        left(180)
        backward(2*length/3)

# Initialize the turtle
initializeTurtle(initial_window_size=(800, 800))

# Set up the turtle's starting position and orientation
jump(400, 750)  # Starting position at the bottom center of the canvas
face(0)
color('red')  # Set the pen color

# Draw the fractal tree
build_cross_3(600)

# Display the drawing
show()

The image below displays the result: a vertically oriented, cross-shaped fractal made of nested, self-similar segments. Each main arm branches into smaller crosses, repeating the same structure at reduced scales. This layered, recursive construction centers around a vertical axis and grows in detail with each level of depth. Rendered in red, the figure exemplifies fractal principles through its balanced symmetry and recursive complexity.

2.2. Second Cross

This second code defines and draws a recursive fractal known as the fourth-order cross using Turtle graphics. The build_cross_4(length) function recursively divides the input length by three and draws four branches, each rotated 90 degrees from the last, creating a cross at each recursion level. The turtle moves forward and backward for each arm, repositioning itself after drawing each segment. The fractal is centered on the canvas, starting at coordinates (400, 400) with a forward-facing orientation and red pen color. The recursive calls repeat until the segment length drops below one, producing increasingly smaller sub-crosses at each level of recursion. 


# Define the fractal cross function
def build_cross_4(length):
    if length > 1:
        build_cross_4(length/3)
        forward(length)
        build_cross_4(length/3)
        backward(length)
        right(90)
        forward(length)
        build_cross_4(length/3)
        backward(length)
        right(90)
        forward(length)
        build_cross_4(length/3)
        backward(length)
        right(90)
        forward(length)
        build_cross_4(length/3)
        backward(length)
        right(90)

# Initialize the turtle
initializeTurtle(initial_window_size=(800, 800))

# Set up the turtle's starting position and orientation
jump(400, 400)  # Starting position at the bottom center of the canvas
face(0)
color('red')  # Set the pen color

# Draw the fractal tree
build_cross_4(250)

# Display the drawing
show()

The image shows the output of the build_cross_4 function, which forms a large central cross with smaller cross patterns embedded at every branching point. Unlike the previous vertically elongated fractal, this figure emphasizes symmetry across both vertical and horizontal axes, creating a balanced and square-like structure. Each arm replicates the same recursive cross pattern at a smaller scale, resulting in dense, regular repetition throughout the figure.

Conclusion

These explorations reinforce the flexibility of fractal algorithms and their relevance in representing natural and abstract structures alike.
